Recursion is rarely a good idea, especially when doing something that is intrinsically non-recursive:<p><pre><code>    char *v = malloc(100000000);
    memset(v, &#x27;-&#x27;, 99999999);
    v[99999999] = 0;
    parseLongSomehow(v);
</code></pre>
What happens?

Why no negative hex?<p>I&#x27;d write something like this:<p><pre><code>  long long parseLongSomehow(char *s) {
      if (isspace(s[0])) {
          return parseLongSomehow(s + 1);
      } else if (s[0] == &#x27;-&#x27;) {
          return -parseLongSomehow(s + 1);
      } else if (s[0] == &#x27;0&#x27; && s[1] == &#x27;x&#x27;) {
          return strtoull(s + 2, 16);
      } else {
          return strtoull(s, 10);
      }
  }
</code></pre>
That doesn&#x27;t handle negative values smaller than LONG_LONG_MIN gracefully, though. Also doesn&#x27;t do error handling.
